"Resco De Dios V., Fischer C., Colinas C.","Climate change effects on mediterranean forests and preventive measures",2007,"New Forests","33","1",,"29","40",,,10.1007/s11056-006-9011-x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33845407999&partnerID=40&md5=8f22d586f9db92dc872915c84db4b182","Àrea de Defensa del Bosc, Centre Tecnològic Forestal de Catalunya, C/ Pujada del Seminari s/n, Solsona (Lleida) E-25280, Spain; Department of Renewable Resources, University of Wyoming, Dept. 3354, 1000 E University Ave, Laramie, WY 82071, United States","Resco De Dios, V., Àrea de Defensa del Bosc, Centre Tecnològic Forestal de Catalunya, C/ Pujada del Seminari s/n, Solsona (Lleida) E-25280, Spain, Department of Renewable Resources, University of Wyoming, Dept. 3354, 1000 E University Ave, Laramie, WY 82071, United States; Fischer, C., Àrea de Defensa del Bosc, Centre Tecnològic Forestal de Catalunya, C/ Pujada del Seminari s/n, Solsona (Lleida) E-25280, Spain; Colinas, C., Àrea de Defensa del Bosc, Centre Tecnològic Forestal de Catalunya, C/ Pujada del Seminari s/n, Solsona (Lleida) E-25280, Spain","This paper synthesizes and reviews literature concerning climate change effects on Mediterranean forest ecology and management as well as the restorative techniques necessary to maintain forest health, forest yield and biodiversity. Climate change compounded with trends of rural abandonment are likely to diminish forested areas within the Mediterranean basin that will be replaced by fire prone shrub communities. This could be favoured by outbreaks of pathogens, fire and other large-scale disturbances. Landscape fragmentation is expected to impede species migration. Annual increments and subsequent income from forests are expected to decrease. Reafforestations are necessary to ensure the presence of propagules of forest species and their site-specific varieties best adapted to future climatic conditions even though they may be different from the present forest-plant community. Current challenges in biodiversity conservation can only be met by afforestations whose main objective is to maintain ecosystem functioning. A new silviculture must emerge encompassing these habitat displacement and economic concerns while maximizing carbon sequestration. © 2006 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.","Biodiversity; Carbon sequestration; Forest restoration; Global warming; Mitigation strategies; Reforestations","Biodiversity; Ecology; Global warming; Reforestation; Carbon sequestration; Forest ecology; Mediterranean forests; Mitigation strategies; Forestry; biodiversity; climate change; climate effect; environmental disturbance; forest ecosystem; forest health; forest management; habitat fragmentation; reforestation; Biodiversity; Ecology; Forestry; Reforestation; Mediterranean Region; Mediterranean Sea",,,,,,"Alfredsson, H., Condron, L.M., Clarholm, M., Davis, M.R., Changes in soil acidity and organic matter following the establishment of conifers on former grassland in New Zealand (1998) For Ecol Manag, 112, pp. 245-252; Alía, R., Martín, S., (2003) EUFORGEN Technical Guidelines for Genetic Conservation and Use for Maritime Pine (Pinus pinaster), p. 6. , International Plant Genetic Resources Institute, Rome, Italy; Allué-Andrade, J.L., Naturaleza, efectos y amortiguamiento del cambio climático en los bosques españoles (1995) Montes, 40, pp. 21-28; Brasier, C.M., Phytophtora cinnamomi and oak decline in southern Europe. Environmental constraints including climate change (1996) Ann For Sci, 53, pp. 347-358; Brown, S., Forests and climate change: Role of forest lands as carbon sinks (1997) Proceedings of the XI World Forestry Congress, 1, pp. 107-121. , Antalya, Turkey; Cámara-Obregón, A., Comportamiento y posibles aplicaciones de Pinus halepensis Mill. en España, frente al cambio climático (1998) Cuadernos de la Sociedad Española de Ciencias Forestales, 7, pp. 51-60; Canadell, J.G., Pataki, D., New advances in carbon cycle research (2002) Trends Eco